    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-12-22T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-12-22T06:00:00-05:00" n="324"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d324">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A4B/589: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-12-22T11:00:00+00:00"
                            >December 22, 1934—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 22—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>951. The information which appeared yesterday on a ticker at the Bourse
                    indicating that France might on its own denounce the Washington Naval Treaty
                    independently of the action of Japan was entirely without foundation. It arose
                    from fact that Foreign Minister Laval and Minister of Marine Piétri were heard
                    by the Foreign Affairs and Naval Committees of the Chamber of Deputies and
                    explained the situation which would be created by Japan’s denunciation which
                    would give France a free hand in the matter of naval building and ratios. It is
                    expected that France will as soon as notified of the denunciation, present a
                    note setting forth its views on ratio limitation particularly with regard to
                    Italy. Laval confirmed this last evening in a conversation with Marriner.</p>
                <p>It was learned indirectly that impression had been given American correspondents
                    that France was happy that Japan had pulled its chestnuts out of the fire.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Straus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
